## Economic Viability and Costs

### Investment Requirements

Transitioning to 100% renewable energy globally or nationally entails substantial upfront investments. The American Action Forum estimates that transitioning the U.S. electricity system to 100% renewables by 2030 would require at least $5.7 trillion, potentially an underestimate as it excludes all contingencies and environmental costs ([Institute for Energy Research, 2019](https://www.instituteforenergyresearch.org/renewable/cost-of-transitioning-to-100-percent-renewable-energy/)).

A global study by Stanford University estimates the total global investment to achieve 100% renewable energy by 2050 at approximately $73 trillion. Despite this high initial cost, the study projects that the investment would pay for itself within seven years due to savings from avoided fossil fuel costs and health benefits ([Yale E360, 2019](https://e360.yale.edu/digest/the-global-price-tag-for-100-percent-renewable-energy-73-trillion)).

### Cost Competitiveness

Modeling studies indicate that 100% renewable energy systems can be cost-competitive with fossil fuel-based systems even before accounting for externalities such as climate change, water use, and pollution. For example, LUT/EWG projects that the levelized cost of electricity (LCOE) for a fully renewable system will decrease slightly from €54/MWh in 2015 to €53/MWh in 2050, while fossil fuel costs are expected to rise due to carbon pricing and resource depletion ([Elliott, 2019](https://physicsworld.com/a/a-global-100-renewable-energy-system/)).

Moreover, conservative technology choices for grid stability (dispatchable capacity, grid expansion, synchronous compensators) add relatively minor costs compared to overall system expenses, supporting the economic viability of renewable systems ([ScienceDirect, 2018](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1364032118303307)).

### Job Creation and Economic Impact

The transition to renewables is expected to generate significant employment opportunities, with projections of 35 million jobs worldwide in the renewable energy sector by 2050, surpassing job losses in fossil fuel industries ([Elliott, 2019](https://physicsworld.com/a/a-global-100-renewable-energy-system/)).

